'''Caicumeo''' or '''Caycumeo''' was the local name of the Camino Real in [[Chiloé Island]]. It crossed through [[Valdivian temperate rainforest|dense forest]] and swamps uniting [[Castro, Chile|Castro]] with [[Ancud]].<ref name=Leon2015/><ref name=Sahady2010>{{cite journal |last=Sahady Villanueva |first=Antonio |last2=Bravo Sánchez |first2=José |last3=Quilodrán Rubio |first3=Carolina |date=2010 |title=Flandes Indiano Chiloense: un patrimonio invencible en el tiempo |url=http://www.anales-ii.ing.uchile.cl/index.php/RU/article/viewFile/11055/11360 |journal=[[Revista de Urbanismo]] |publisher= |volume=23 |issue= |pages=1–27 |doi= |access-date=30 January 2016 |language=Spanish}}</ref> The road was opened in 1788.<ref name=Leon2015/> According to local lore the name would derive from a villager who cleared the track with the solely aided by a [[machete]].<ref name=Leon2015>{{cite journal |last=León León |first=Marco Antonio |date=2015 |title=Una Provincia "Enteramente Insular": Geografía, exploraciones y cotidianeidad en Chiloé Republicano, Chile (1826-1900) |url=http://www.scielo.cl/scielo.php?pid=S0718-22442015000100004&script=sci_arttext |journal=[[Magallania]] |publisher= |volume=43 |issue=1 |pages= |doi= |access-date=30 January 2016}}</ref> The road was established following the Spanish founded the "city-fort" of Ancud in northern Chiloé leading to increased trade and agricultural expansion.<ref name=Sahady2010/><ref name=Urbina2014>{{cite journal |last=Urbina Carrasco |first=María Ximena |date=2014 |title=El frustrado fuerte de Tenquehuen en el archipiélago de los Chonos, 1750: Dimensión chilota de un conflicto hispano-británico  |url=http://www.scielo.cl/scielo.php?pid=S0717-71942014000100006&script=sci_arttext |journal=[[Historia (Chilean journal)|Historia]] |publisher= |volume=47 |issue=I |pages= |doi= |access-date=28 January 2016}}</ref>

