[[File:Union Banks en.svg|thumb|Sin Cowe Island in the Union Banks]]

'''Sin Cowe Island''', also known as '''Sinh Ton Island''',<ref>{{cite book |last1=Valencia |first1=Mark J. |last2=Van Dyke |first2=Jon M. |last3=Ludwig |first3=Noel A. |title=Sharing the Resources of the South China Sea |date=July 1999 |publisher=University of Hawaii Press |location=Honolulu |isbn=0824818814 |page=31 |url=https://books.google.com.ph/books?id=gqOKE2aI5roC&pg=PA31&dq=sin+cowe+island&hl=en&sa=X&ei=GiaRU6mjMY_78QXclYLIAw&ved=0CC4Q6AEwAQ#v=onepage&q=sin%20cowe%20island&f=false |accessdate=6 June 2014}}</ref> ({{lang-vi|Đảo Sinh Tồn}}; {{zh|c=景宏岛|p=Jinghong Dao}}; {{lang-tl|Rurok}}) is an [[island]] in the [[Spratly Islands]] in the [[South China Sea]]. With an area of {{convert|8|ha|acres|abbr=off}}, it is the [[List of Spratly Islands by area|seventh largest]] Spratly island and the third largest of those occupied by Vietnam. It has a fringing reef which is above water at low tide.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Cole|first1=Bernard |title=The Great Wall at Sea: China's Navy Enters the Twenty-first Century |date=1 October 2001 |publisher=U.S. Naval Institute Press |isbn= 1557502390 |page= 207 |edition= First |url= https://books.google.com.ph/books?id=ikj0ZahQDIYC&pg=PA207&lpg=PA207&dq=sin+cowe+island+news&source=bl&ots=1OKXfsM-vD&sig=N8vn5PSkrucVArK5meUemeQbkXU&hl=en&sa=X&ei=OCSRU_bKKJTl8AXi0YDwBQ&ved=0CGcQ6AEwCQ#v=onepage&q=cowesin%20cowe%20island%20news&f=false |accessdate=6 June 2014}}</ref>

This island has been controlled by Vietnam since 1974, first by the [[South Vietnam]]'s [[ARVN]] Navy, followed by the Navy of the [[Socialist Republic of Vietnam]] after 1975. The island is also claimed by [[China]], the [[Philippines]] and [[Taiwan]].

It is part of the [[Union Banks]].<ref name=Gazetteer>{{cite web | title = Digital Gazetteer of Spratly Islands | url = http://www.southchinasea.org/2011/08/19/digital-gazetteer-of-the-spratly-islands/ |date= 19 August 2011 | accessdate = 5 June 2014 |publisher= www.southchinasea.org }}</ref>

== Topography and Structures ==
Sin Cowe island is inhabited by Vietnamese soldiers. The structures on it include a two-storied government building, anti aircraft guns, artillery and a Vietnamese Sovereignty marker.<ref>{{cite web |title=Photos of Sin Cowe island |url= http://southseaconversations.wordpress.com/2012/06/14/adventure-regret-anger-one-global-times-reporters-epic-south-china-sea-journey/ |publisher=South sea conversations |date= 14 June 2012 |accessdate=6 June 2014}}</ref>

