{{coord|9.885|114.33|display=title}}

{{multiple image | align = right | direction = vertical | width = 220 | image1 = GOPR0292 DK edit.jpg | alt1 = | caption1 = {{center|Groove formation}} | image2 = GOPR0294 DK edit.jpg | alt2 = | caption2 = {{center|Spur formation}} }}
'''Spur and groove formations''' are a [[geomorphic]] feature of many [[coral reef]]s. They are ridges of reef formed by [[coral]] "spurs" separated by channels "grooves" which often have sediment or rubble bed. Spur and groove formations vary in their size and distribution worldwide but are a common feature on many forereefs of [[fringing reef]]s, [[barrier reefs]], and [[atolls]] which are exposed to moderate wave energy.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Storlazzi|first1=Curt|title=Quantitative morphology of a fringing reef tract from high-resolution laser bathymetry: Southern Molokai, Hawaii|journal=Geol. Soc. Am. Bull|date=2003|url=http://gsabulletin.gsapubs.org/content/115/11/1344.short |volume=115 |issue=11 |pages=1344–1355 |doi=10.1130/B25200.1}}</ref> Spur and groove formations are influenced by the incoming [[surface wave]]s, and the waves induce a circulation pattern of counter rotating circulation cells.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Rogers|first1=Justin|title=Hydrodynamics of spur and groove formations on a coral reef |journal=J. Geophys. Res.|url=http://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/10.1002/jgrc.20225/full |date=2013 |volume=118 |issue=6 |pages=3059–3073 |doi=10.1002/jgrc.20225}}</ref>
The alongshore shape of spur and groove formations varies from smoothly varying rounded spurs, to flat spurs with shallow rectangular grooves, or deeply cut rectangular or overhanging channels sometimes called buttresses. Spur and groove formations have typical scales of: spur height 0.5 to 10 m, alongshore wavelength 5 to 150 m, width of groove 1 to 100 m, and found in depths from 0 to 30 m. The mechanism for maintaining preferential coral growth on the spur is thought to be caused by higher wave stress on the spur which causes sediment to be shed towards the groove and downslope and preferential [[coral]] growth on the spur.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Rogers|first1=Justin|title=Field observations of wave‐driven circulation over spur and groove formations on a coral reef|url=http://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/10.1002/2014JC010464/full |journal=Journal of Geophysical Research: Oceans|date=2015|volume=118 |issue=6 |pages=3059–3073 |doi=10.1002/2014JC010464}}</ref> Thus, it is believed that spur and grooves are essentially constructional in formation, while a less important mechanism may occur from sediment scour in the grooves.
== See also== *[[Coastal morphodynamics]] *[[Coral reef]] *[[Coastal geography]] *[[Fringing reef]]
