This is a '''timeline of [[healthcare in the Democratic Republic of the Congo]]'''. Major events such as policies and organizations are described.
==Big picture== {| class="sortable wikitable" ! Year/period !! Key developments |- |15th century||First contact of Congo area with European medicine comes along with [[Portuguese discoveries|Portuguese explorers]].<ref name="Democratic Republic of Congo profile - Timeline" /> |- |19th century||[[Leopold II of Belgium]] colonizes the Congo and exploits the region as his private property. Millions of people are estimated to die due to exploitation and mistreat by Leopold's agents.<ref name="Democratic Republic of Congo profile - Timeline" /><ref>{{cite news|title=King Leopold's legacy of DR Congo violence|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/africa/3516965.stm|accessdate=12 October 2016}}</ref> |- |20th century||Congo gains autonomy early in the century, and becomes an independent country in the 1960s. Periodic wars, famines and epidemics ravage the health of the population across the century. [[AIDS]] epidemic breaks out in the last decades. <ref name="Democratic Republic of Congo profile - Timeline" /> |- |Recent years||Today, the [[Democratic Republic of the Congo]] has one of the worst health indices in the world. Malaria is the greatest threat to health. Water-borne diseases such as [[diarrhoea]], [[schistosomiasis]] and [[cholera]] are also common. The [[WHO]] calculates only 1 doctor and 5 nurses/midwives for every 10,000 people for the period 2000-2010.<ref name="Poverty & Healthcare" /> |}
==Full timeline== {| class="sortable wikitable" ! Year/period !! Type of event !! Event !!Location |- |1908||Background||[[Congo Free State]] is placed under rule of [[Belgium]].<ref name="Democratic Republic of Congo profile - Timeline" />|| |- |1912||Organization||[[Kinshasa General Hospital]] is founded.<ref>{{cite web|title=In the Heart of Africa, Darkness|url=http://partners.nytimes.com/library/world/africa/040600africa-diamonds-side.html|accessdate=10 October 2016}}</ref>||[[Kinshasa]] |- |1925||Development||Medical missionary Dr. [[Arthur Lewis Piper]] first brings and uses [[tryparsamide]], the Rockefeller Foundation’s drug to cure [[african trypanosomiasis]], to the Congo.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Klingman |first=Jack |title=Arthur Lewis Piper, M.D.: A Medical Missionary in the Belgian Congo |journal=Journal of Community Health |volume=19 |issue=2 |year=1994 |pages=125–146 |doi=10.1007/BF02260364 }}</ref> |- |1928||Organization||Ngaliema Clinic is founded.<ref name="Monkole and Ngaliema: Two referral hospitals in DRC">{{cite web|title=Monkole and Ngaliema: Two referral hospitals in DRC|url=http://www.afd.fr/lang/en/home/pays/afrique/geo-afr/republique-democratique-du-congo?actuCtnId=114814|accessdate=10 October 2016}}</ref>||[[Ngaliema]] |- |1955||Discovery||The first case of [[HIV]] infection in a human is identified in the [[Democratic Republic of the Congo|DRC]].<ref>{{cite web|title=The History of HIV|url=http://www.healthline.com/health/hiv-aids/history#EarliestCase1|accessdate=11 October 2016}}</ref>|| |- |1960||Background||Congo becomes an independent country, with [[Patrice Lumumba]] as prime minister and [[Joseph Kasavubu]] as president.<ref name="Democratic Republic of Congo profile - Timeline">{{cite web|title=Democratic Republic of Congo profile - Timeline|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-africa-13286306|accessdate=11 October 2016}}</ref>|| |- |1984||Campaign||[[Project SIDA]] is launched in the [[Democratic Republic of the Congo|DRC]] as a scientific organization with the purpose of studying [[AIDS]] in Africa. Project SIDA scientists are among the first to document heterosexual transmission of AIDS and the existence of AIDS outside of developed countries. It is the largest HIV/AIDS research project on the continent during the 1980s.<ref>{{cite web|title=AIDS: the Early Years and CDC's Response|url=https://www.cdc.gov/mmwr/preview/mmwrhtml/su6004a11.htm|accessdate=10 October 2016}}</ref>||[[Kinshasa]] (headquarters) |- |1991||Organization||[[Monkole Hospital]] is founded.<ref name="Monkole and Ngaliema: Two referral hospitals in DRC" />||[[Kinshasa]] |- |1994||Crisis||[[Cholera]] epidemic breaks out in the [[Democratic Republic of the Congo|DRC]]. During the worst period, it is estimated that as many as 3,000 people were dying per day from cholera.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Echenberg|first1=Myron|title=Africa in the Time of Cholera: A History of Pandemics from 1817 to the Present|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=3cQoi8S-wk4C&lpg=PP1&dq=africa+in+the+time+of+cholera&pg=PP1&redir_esc=y#v=onepage&q&f=false|accessdate=10 October 2016}}</ref>||[[Goma]] |- |1997||Organization||The Institute for Higher Studies in Nursing (ISSI) is established by the Congolese cultural centre for training and development (CECFOR).<ref>{{cite web|title=Institut Supérieur en Sciences Infirmières (ISSI)|url=http://www.lincco.org/en/d-r-of-congo|accessdate=10 October 2016}}</ref>||[[Kinshasa]] |- |1999||Organization||[[Panzi Hospital]] is founded.<ref>{{cite web|title=Panzi Hospital|url=http://www.panzifoundation.org/panzi-hospital/|accessdate=10 October 2016}}</ref>||[[Bukavu]], [[Sud-Kivu]] |- |1999||Organization||[[International Medical Corps]] (a global humanitarian nonprofit organization established by volunteer doctors and nurses) begins working in the [[Democratic Republic of the Congo|DRC]].<ref>{{cite web|title=International Medical Corps|url=https://internationalmedicalcorps.org/drc|accessdate=11 October 2016}}</ref>|| |- |2006||Policy||New constitution makes several institutional reforms. Provinces gain the authority to hire and manage the health workforce; develop, support, and supervise health programs consistent with the national health development plan; manage hospital, laboratory, and pharmaceutical services; promote primary health care services at the facility and community levels; and disseminate and enforce health laws and regulations.<ref>{{cite web|title=HFG at Work in the Democratic Republic of the Congo|url=https://www.hfgproject.org/where-we-work/africa/drc/|accessdate=11 October 2016}}</ref>|| |- |2006||Campaign||The Congolese government starts to take integrated approach to tackling [[malaria]], including distribution of insecticide-treated bed nets across the country.<ref>{{cite web|title=Malaria still biggest killer|url=http://www.irinnews.org/report/77948/drc-malaria-still-biggest-killer|accessdate=12 October 2016}}</ref>|| |- |2008||Organization||[[Fistula Care Plus]] (a five-year [[fistula]] repair and prevention project from the U.S. Agency for International Development [[USAID]]) starts its operations in the [[Democratic Republic of the Congo|DRC]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Fistula Care|url=https://fistulacare.org/countries/drc/|accessdate=11 October 2016}}</ref>|| |- |2009||Report||Over 6.7 million cases of [[malaria]] are reported in the [[Democratic Republic of the Congo|DRC]]. Two out of every five deaths among young children are caused by malaria.<ref name="Poverty & Healthcare">{{cite web|title=Poverty & Healthcare|url=http://www.our-africa.org/democratic-republic-of-congo/poverty-healthcare|accessdate=10 October 2016}}</ref>|| |- |2010||Crisis||Measles epidemic breaks out in the [[Democratic Republic of the Congo|DRC]]. Massive campaign vaccinates more than 14 million children.<ref>{{cite web|title=Democratic Republic of Congo: Condition still critical|url=http://www.msf.org/en/article/democratic-republic-congo-condition-still-critical|accessdate=12 October 2016}}</ref>|| |- |2011||Campaign||A new vaccine to prevent [[pneumococcal disease]] is introduced through aid from [[Global Alliance for Vaccines]].<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/04/12/health/12global.html?_r=1&partner=rss&emc=rss|work=The New York Times|first=Donald G.|last=McNeil Jr|title=Congo, With Donors' Help, Introduces New Vaccine for Pneumococcal Disease|date=11 April 2011}}</ref>||[[Kinshasa]] |- |2011||Crisis||Between 430,000 and 560,000 cases of [[HIV]] are reported in the DRC.<ref>{{cite web|title=UNAIDS REPORT ON THE GLOBAL AIDS EPIDEMIC 2010|url=http://www.unaids.org/globalreport/documents/20101123_GlobalReport_full_en.pdf|accessdate=12 October 2016}}</ref>|| |- |2012||Report||46 percent of the population are reported to have access to an [[Improved water source|improved drinking water]] source in the [[Democratic Republic of the Congo|DRC]].<ref>={{Cite web|url=https://www.imf.org/external/pubs/ft/sdn/2015/sdn1511tn.pdf|title=Issues in managing water challenges and policy instruments: Regional perspectives and case studies.|last=|first=|date=2015|website=|publisher=International Monetary Fund|access-date=12 October 2016}}</ref> Also, [[sanitation]] coverage is estimated at only 31 percent in 2012.<ref name=":5">{{Cite web|url=http://data.un.org/CountryProfile.aspx?crName=Democratic%20Republic%20of%20the%20Congo|title=UN Data. Democratic Republic of Congo.|last=|first=|date=|website=|publisher=|access-date=2016-05-27}}</ref> |- |2014||Crisis||[[Ebola]] virus disease [[2014 Democratic Republic of the Congo Ebola virus outbreak|breaks out]] in the [[Democratic Republic of the Congo|DRC]]. 49 deaths are reported.<ref>{{cite web|title=EBOLA RESPONSE ROADM AP SITUATION REPORT|url=http://apps.who.int/iris/bitstream/10665/137424/1/roadmapsitrep_31Oct2014_eng.pdf?ua=1&ua=1|accessdate=10 October 2016}}</ref>|| |- |2016||Report||Life expectancy in the [[Democratic Republic of the Congo|DRC]] is estimated at 57.32 years, being ranked 205th out of 228 political subdivisions.<ref>{{cite web|title=Life Expectancy|url=http://www.geoba.se/population.php?pc=world&type=015&year=2016&st=rank&asde=d&page=1|accessdate=10 October 2016}}</ref>|| |}
